[boy reading] "The boy with fair
hair lowered himself down

252
00:16:15,516 --> 00:16:16,684
the last few feet of rock.

253
00:16:16,934 --> 00:16:18,894
and began to pick his way
toward the lagoon.

254
00:16:19,228 --> 00:16:21,105
Though he had taken off his school sweater

255
00:16:21,188 --> 00:16:22,356
and trailed it now from one hand,

256
00:16:22,439 --> 00:16:23,816
his gray shirt stuck to him..."

257
00:16:26,568 --> 00:16:27,569
[knocking on the door]

258
00:16:27,778 --> 00:16:28,862
Go away!

259
00:16:29,154 --> 00:16:30,239
Thank you.

260
00:16:32,032 --> 00:16:32,991
Wow!

261
00:16:33,784 --> 00:16:36,620
Uh, sorry, sir.

262
00:16:36,745 --> 00:16:38,956
I thought you were a pupil.

263
00:16:40,040 --> 00:16:40,958
No.

264
00:16:43,293 --> 00:16:45,129
What's with the Berlin Wall?

265
00:16:45,879 --> 00:16:47,297
That's a matter of necessity.

266
00:16:48,382 --> 00:16:49,216
Right.

267
00:16:50,676 --> 00:16:51,885
Who's your roommate?

268
00:16:52,261 --> 00:16:54,221
Oh, uh, honestly, I don't know.

269
00:16:55,347 --> 00:16:56,265
Right.

270
00:16:56,390 --> 00:16:58,183
Well I've got a delivery for, uh...

271
00:17:02,396 --> 00:17:04,189
No way you can make him feel welcome, huh?

272
00:17:04,398 --> 00:17:07,735
Yeah, see he's a rugby player so believe
me, my friendship would be a hindrance.

273
00:17:08,277 --> 00:17:10,654
That's quite a persecution complex
you've got going on there.

274
00:17:11,113 --> 00:17:12,072
Thank you.

275
00:17:12,740 --> 00:17:13,866
You gonna let me hear something?

276
00:17:14,032 --> 00:17:15,492
Well, I can't play

277
00:17:15,701 --> 00:17:17,870
and even if I could I don't think
I'd play anything you like.

278
00:17:19,163 --> 00:17:20,289
[whispering] Just play something.

279
00:17:35,554 --> 00:17:38,057
-Okay, so that's 'D.'
-That's 'D.'

280
00:17:42,436 --> 00:17:44,396
-Is 'D' your only--
-D's my only chord, yeah.

281
00:17:44,480 --> 00:17:45,481
I see. Okay, well...

282
00:17:46,148 --> 00:17:48,609
Lift your finger up to that one.

283
00:17:49,902 --> 00:17:50,944
There.

284
00:17:51,278 --> 00:17:52,488
Yep. Now play.

285
00:17:55,157 --> 00:17:57,076
[whispering] Now you know another chord.

286
00:17:58,911 --> 00:17:59,745
See ya.

287
00:18:00,871 --> 00:18:01,955
[door closes]

288
00:18:03,665 --> 00:18:04,541
[coach whistle blowing]

289
00:18:04,625 --> 00:18:05,584
[guitar strumming]

290
00:18:07,044 --> 00:18:09,797
[strumming between two chords]

291
00:18:19,348 --> 00:18:21,934
Sir, I'm really, really sorry.
I know I'm late.

292
00:18:22,059 --> 00:18:23,685
[stammering] It's just...
I couldn't find my boots.

293
00:18:23,769 --> 00:18:26,313
I thought I put them in my bag and I
thought my bag was in my classroom.

294
00:18:26,396 --> 00:18:28,690
-But--
-Conor, relax.

295
00:18:29,525 --> 00:18:31,735
You're new. It happens.

296
00:18:32,986 --> 00:18:34,446
The lads are running drills out there.

297
00:18:34,780 --> 00:18:38,242
Get ready, I'll go out with you.
Get you introduced.

298
00:18:41,995 --> 00:18:43,831
[Pascal] Once you cross
that white line, Conor,

299
00:18:44,289 --> 00:18:46,458
I want you to concentrate
on just one thing.

300
00:18:48,794 --> 00:18:50,045
Express yourself.

301
00:18:53,340 --> 00:18:55,259
-Good to go?
-Yeah.

302
00:18:56,468 --> 00:18:57,386
After you.

303
00:19:01,014 --> 00:19:04,059
[two chords strumming]

304
00:19:10,023 --> 00:19:12,526
Everyone, this is Conor.

305
00:19:13,443 --> 00:19:15,737
Conor won the Junior Cup
with St. Bart's last year,

306
00:19:15,821 --> 00:19:18,407
kicking nineteen points
in the final, was it?

307
00:19:19,992 --> 00:19:22,494
I asked him up with us seniors
so he sees what we're made of.

308
00:19:23,120 --> 00:19:24,663
Give him something to aspire to.

309
00:19:25,289 --> 00:19:27,374
Also, give Wallace a bit of competition.

310
00:19:27,666 --> 00:19:28,876
You've met our captain, Victor.

311
00:19:28,959 --> 00:19:31,712
Apart from him far too many names to
remember but I'll give you the gist,

312
00:19:32,045 --> 00:19:33,547
Kieth Chappy, prop.

313
00:19:34,173 --> 00:19:36,216
Tom Quinlin, current place kicker.

314
00:19:36,466 --> 00:19:38,719
We get our speed from this fella.

315
00:19:39,094 --> 00:19:41,805
Scrum half one, two...

316
00:19:42,764 --> 00:19:43,932
Chief wrecking ball.

317
00:19:46,101 --> 00:19:49,021
Okay, line out, first against seconds.

318
00:19:49,104 --> 00:19:50,480
Conor, play at 10 for the firsts.

319
00:19:50,898 --> 00:19:54,026
-Wallace-- where's Wally?
-I'm here.

320
00:19:55,027 --> 00:19:55,861
Defend it.

321
00:19:57,779 --> 00:19:59,239
Don't worry, Wally. I got you.

322
00:20:00,866 --> 00:20:02,534
["Thirteen" playing]

323
00:20:02,618 --> 00:20:03,702
[coach commands]

324
00:20:04,036 --> 00:20:05,120
[coach whistles]

325
00:20:05,203 --> 00:20:07,581
♪ ...walk you home from school ♪

326
00:20:11,418 --> 00:20:16,298
♪ Won't you let me 
Meet you at the pool ♪

327
00:20:20,427 --> 00:20:23,847
♪ Maybe Friday I can ♪

328
00:20:25,265 --> 00:20:26,808
You're an animal!

329
00:20:28,060 --> 00:20:29,728
[Weasel] You're a fucking monster!

330
00:20:32,898 --> 00:20:34,524
Wallace, come back in for Conor.

331
00:20:34,691 --> 00:20:36,485
Conor, take a break.

332
00:20:36,902 --> 00:20:38,403
Take a break?

333
00:20:39,696 --> 00:20:41,156
We've only just begun.

334
00:20:43,325 --> 00:20:44,993
Okay. Reset!

335
00:20:45,327 --> 00:20:48,163
♪ Won't you tell your dad
Get off my back ♪

336
00:20:52,125 --> 00:20:57,256
♪ Tell him what we said 
'Bout 'Paint It Black' ♪

337
00:21:00,801 --> 00:21:04,721
♪ Rock 'n Roll is here to stay ♪

338
00:21:05,138 --> 00:21:08,642
♪ Come inside where it's okay ♪

339
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:17,025
♪ And I'll shake you ♪

340
00:21:23,448 --> 00:21:26,451
-Is it broken?
-Of course it's fucken broken!

341
00:21:26,910 --> 00:21:29,037
Well done lads. Well played.

342
00:21:29,371 --> 00:21:32,082
And don't worry about that, Weasel,
you were never a looker.

343
00:21:32,290 --> 00:21:33,500
[boys laughing]

344
00:21:33,583 --> 00:21:35,502
Anyone see Conor Masters?

345
00:21:36,086 --> 00:21:37,170
He never came in.

346
00:21:47,264 --> 00:21:51,601
♪ Won't you tell me 
What you're thinking of ♪

347
00:21:53,311 --> 00:21:55,564
[Sherry] "Reveal to me
who are you" I said.

348
00:21:57,441 --> 00:22:00,485
I set an essay title for you because I
wanted to find out about you

349
00:22:00,569 --> 00:22:02,571
and there are some excellent essays.

350
00:22:03,238 --> 00:22:05,574
But there was one that
stood out above all.

351
00:22:07,117 --> 00:22:08,285
Ned Roche,

352
00:22:09,536 --> 00:22:11,705
do you want to get up here
and read it in front of the class?

353
00:22:12,205 --> 00:22:13,498
I'm actually okay...

354
00:22:14,583 --> 00:22:15,584
thanks.

355
00:22:16,752 --> 00:22:18,378
I mean, thank you, but um...

356
00:22:18,754 --> 00:22:20,047
I'd just prefer not to.

357
00:22:20,672 --> 00:22:21,673
I can appreciate that.

358
00:22:24,926 --> 00:22:25,927
But I think you should.

359
00:22:29,765 --> 00:22:31,391
[boys purr together]

360
00:22:31,516 --> 00:22:35,520
The next person to make a single solitary
sound of any sort is in hideous trouble.

361
00:22:38,106 --> 00:22:39,357
Good. Ned.

362
00:22:56,541 --> 00:22:57,751
[Ned reading] "A Family Member.

363
00:22:59,169 --> 00:23:01,296
I have this cousin whose name's Kevin.

364
00:23:01,922 --> 00:23:03,632
And I'm pretty sure he's
destined for Heaven.

365
00:23:04,591 --> 00:23:06,343
He's always spotlessly dressed.

366
00:23:07,135 --> 00:23:09,805
Clean and neat and totally smooth.

367
00:23:10,263 --> 00:23:11,264
He likes to wear this...

368
00:23:11,556 --> 00:23:13,934
-[rock music blaring]
-fur lined, sheepskin jacket--"

369
00:23:16,728 --> 00:23:18,396
Keep going, please.

370
00:23:21,900 --> 00:23:23,693
"...Kevin were just not the same.

371
00:23:24,194 --> 00:23:25,904
Oh my perfect cousin.

372
00:23:27,697 --> 00:23:29,032
...he doesn't.

373
00:23:30,158 --> 00:23:32,244
He's his father's pride and joy.

374
00:23:32,536 --> 00:23:35,330
His mother's little golden boy.

375
00:23:37,582 --> 00:23:38,959
...economics.

376
00:23:39,626 --> 00:23:40,961
[all laughing]

377
00:23:41,044 --> 00:23:42,838
...physics and bionics.

378
00:23:43,380 --> 00:23:46,007
He thinks that I'm a bit of a cabbage.

379
00:23:46,299 --> 00:23:48,301
-Cos I hate university--"
-Stop, stop, stop.

380
00:23:49,845 --> 00:23:50,887
Sit down.

381
00:24:03,358 --> 00:24:05,652
Listen to you, the baying crowd.

382
00:24:06,570 --> 00:24:07,988
Bleating like sheep.

383
00:24:10,198 --> 00:24:12,492
Why do you assume that
this lesson isn't for you?

384
00:24:18,165 --> 00:24:22,377
Never, ever, ever use a borrowed voice!

385
00:24:26,089 --> 00:24:28,216
-You're all individuals--
-[school bell rings]

386
00:24:34,764 --> 00:24:36,308
Stop! Stop!

387
00:24:40,645 --> 00:24:43,523
If you spend your whole life being
someone else, who's going to be you?

388
00:24:48,486 --> 00:24:49,446
Get out!

389
00:25:16,097 --> 00:25:17,057
[Conor clears his throat]

390
00:25:19,768 --> 00:25:20,727
[clears his throat louder]

391
00:25:22,896 --> 00:25:25,357
-I'll turn it down.
-No, not that.

392
00:25:29,361 --> 00:25:31,196
Today, that was pretty cool.

393
00:25:32,280 --> 00:25:33,406
I liked the song.

394
00:25:34,157 --> 00:25:35,700
Could you go straight to hell please?

395
00:25:36,618 --> 00:25:37,869
I liked it. A lot.

396
00:25:40,497 --> 00:25:41,873
Why do you like so much old stuff?

397
00:25:43,708 --> 00:25:46,044
Well, because modern life is rubbish.

398
00:25:47,337 --> 00:25:48,213
I hear that.

399
00:25:56,972 --> 00:25:58,098
So I saw Weasel's face.

400
00:25:59,849 --> 00:26:02,352
-How did you know I did that?
-Word gets around.

401
00:26:03,311 --> 00:26:04,354
Even to me.

402
00:26:09,276 --> 00:26:10,694
Can I ask you a question?

403
00:26:14,572 --> 00:26:16,116
It's personal.

404
00:26:23,581 --> 00:26:24,749
Are you gay?

405
00:26:26,293 --> 00:26:29,045
Don't worry, Conor. I'm not going to
"bum you" in the night. All right.

406
00:26:29,129 --> 00:26:30,797
-No, sorry. I--
-Was that it?

407
00:26:31,923 --> 00:26:33,258
That was your question, was it?

408
00:26:50,066 --> 00:26:51,526
It's not really the music.

409
00:26:52,652 --> 00:26:53,820
It's more the story.

410
00:26:54,779 --> 00:26:56,781
How someone can write about
themselves like that,

411
00:26:56,990 --> 00:26:57,949
about their family.

412
00:27:00,160 --> 00:27:01,202
It's mad, isn't it?

413
00:27:01,369 --> 00:27:03,330
Well, yeah. The madder the better.

414
00:27:08,835 --> 00:27:10,545
[old rock music playing softly]

415
00:27:16,843 --> 00:27:19,179
So you're not just taking the piss?

416
00:27:21,848 --> 00:27:23,308
I liked the song.

417
00:27:25,935 --> 00:27:27,020
All right, follow me, then.

418
00:27:30,690 --> 00:27:32,400
[music playing louder]

419
00:27:49,125 --> 00:27:50,502
[music becoming faint]

420
00:27:55,465 --> 00:27:56,800
I didn't know this was here.

421
00:27:59,844 --> 00:28:00,845
I found these last year.

422
00:28:02,055 --> 00:28:02,972
Vinyl.

423
00:28:04,641 --> 00:28:05,725
[Ned] Look at those faces.

424
00:28:06,351 --> 00:28:07,352
[Conor] What were they thinking?

425
00:28:08,144 --> 00:28:09,062
Well...

426
00:28:09,270 --> 00:28:11,689
none of them ever cared about the
stuff that matters here, that's for sure.

427
00:28:18,655 --> 00:28:20,156
Man, I can't wait to get out of here.

428
00:28:21,324 --> 00:28:22,534
What are you going to be?

429
00:28:22,826 --> 00:28:25,578
I am basically unemployable,
but I'll be free.

430
00:28:27,205 --> 00:28:29,249
My Dad and I used to sail, before he...

431
00:28:30,208 --> 00:28:31,960
before he became interested
in other things.

432
00:28:32,710 --> 00:28:34,421
I remember sitting
at the front of the boat.

433
00:28:34,838 --> 00:28:37,006
That felt free. Flying...

434
00:28:37,757 --> 00:28:38,842
You still got the boat?

435
00:28:39,551 --> 00:28:41,594
It's still there, I think. Rusting away.

436
00:28:41,803 --> 00:28:43,263
So, what's it like to punch
someone in the face?

437
00:28:46,975 --> 00:28:49,769
Whoa, show me that.
How do you know a chord?

438
00:28:50,145 --> 00:28:52,814
I can like music, you know.
We're not all the same.

439
00:28:53,356 --> 00:28:54,649
So you don't have a "Shit List"?

440
00:28:57,235 --> 00:28:58,778
I think you've been taken off that list.

441
00:29:02,949 --> 00:29:05,034
[strumming new chord]

442
00:29:19,299 --> 00:29:22,177
[Ned] I never knew I had been 
lonely until I found a friend.

443
00:29:22,719 --> 00:29:25,138
Not that Conor and I were peas in a pod.

444
00:29:25,305 --> 00:29:27,682
I mean, I'd never met someone 
who liked to run around

445
00:29:27,766 --> 00:29:31,895
as much as I liked to sit down 
and do nothing at all.

446
00:29:32,937 --> 00:29:36,941
My defenses were coming down 
and - I'd never say it out loud,

447
00:29:37,817 --> 00:29:39,444
but it felt pretty good.

448
00:29:40,570 --> 00:29:44,616
Weasel had suddenly stopped bullying me
and I no longer dreamed of being expelled.

449
00:29:47,327 --> 00:29:48,995
Despite my best intentions,

450
00:29:49,370 --> 00:29:50,997
I began to feel like I fit in.

451
00:29:51,831 --> 00:29:52,790
All packed?

452
00:29:53,833 --> 00:29:55,084
Yeah.

453
00:29:55,460 --> 00:29:56,461
What happened?

454
00:29:57,253 --> 00:29:58,797
-I was pocketed.
-Again?

455
00:29:59,130 --> 00:30:00,632
How many times is that since September?

456
00:30:01,424 --> 00:30:04,636
Err, three... no-- four.

457
00:30:05,345 --> 00:30:06,554
Yeah. How many have you had?

458
00:30:07,305 --> 00:30:08,389
I've never been pocketed.

459
00:30:09,057 --> 00:30:11,684
-You've never been pocketed?
-I've never been pocketed.

460
00:30:12,310 --> 00:30:13,478
That's not right.

461
00:30:14,646 --> 00:30:16,856
Anyway, this is for you.

462
00:30:17,899 --> 00:30:18,983
What is it?

463
00:30:19,567 --> 00:30:20,401
A birthday present.

464
00:30:22,278 --> 00:30:23,279
Really?

465
00:30:23,655 --> 00:30:24,864
Yeah. Well...

466
00:30:25,532 --> 00:30:27,784
I wasn't going to get you
anything, obviously, but...

467
00:30:28,117 --> 00:30:30,954
my wicked stepmother said seeing as
we're roommates and all, you know,

468
00:30:31,621 --> 00:30:33,748
probably should - it's a harmonica.

469
00:30:35,708 --> 00:30:36,751
Thanks, Ned.

470
00:30:37,710 --> 00:30:40,922
Oh, I have one more present
for you actually. Yeah...

471
00:30:43,675 --> 00:30:45,969
-You wouldn't dare.
-Wouldn't I, though?

472
00:30:46,344 --> 00:30:47,178
Ned...

473
00:30:49,055 --> 00:30:50,557
Have a good birthday.

474
00:30:52,058 --> 00:30:53,226
Bastard...

475
00:30:57,647 --> 00:30:59,440
Alas, poor Yorick!

476
00:31:00,483 --> 00:31:02,277
I knew him, Horatio,

477
00:31:04,112 --> 00:31:05,738
a fellow of infinite jest...

478
00:31:06,656 --> 00:31:09,367
[Ned] Mr. Sherry began 
to work with us as a team.

479
00:31:10,368 --> 00:31:11,995
And we all loved him for it.

480
00:31:12,829 --> 00:31:14,706
[speaking indistinctly]

481
00:31:16,875 --> 00:31:21,004
Still, when an annual variety show was
announced at the local girl's school

482
00:31:21,170 --> 00:31:23,047
no one stuck their hands up.

483
00:31:23,590 --> 00:31:26,926
But Sherry had heard us messing around
on those old guitars and said--

484
00:31:27,176 --> 00:31:30,346
no, insisted that Conor
and I should play a song.

485
00:31:32,557 --> 00:31:35,101
[playing guitar]

486
00:31:43,276 --> 00:31:44,485
All right, fellas. How's it going?

487
00:31:44,569 --> 00:31:46,029
-Extremely bad.
-Awful, thanks.

488
00:31:47,572 --> 00:31:49,157
-And why is that?
-Well...

489
00:31:49,282 --> 00:31:52,952
we're not these deadly Spanish guitar
players, so we can't do an instrumental.

490
00:31:53,661 --> 00:31:57,206
We have to do a song, but neither
of us wants to be the singer.

491
00:31:57,624 --> 00:31:59,792
-I'm definitely not doing it.
-No. Me neither.

492
00:32:00,043 --> 00:32:01,544
Why not both of you?

493
00:32:01,836 --> 00:32:03,463
What, like Simon &amp; Garfunkel?

494
00:32:04,797 --> 00:32:06,257
Yeah, like Simon &amp; Garfunkel.

495
00:32:07,258 --> 00:32:08,343
[Ned laughing nervously]

496
00:32:08,635 --> 00:32:09,636
I don't think so.

497
00:32:09,928 --> 00:32:11,763
Not cool enough for you, Ned, no?

498
00:32:11,888 --> 00:32:13,848
Honestly no, not really.

499
00:32:14,891 --> 00:32:18,102
Well you, young man, need to learn about

500
00:32:18,436 --> 00:32:20,939
what is much more important than cool.

501
00:32:21,940 --> 00:32:23,316
And that is...

502
00:32:28,613 --> 00:32:29,739
what is beautiful.

503
00:32:30,365 --> 00:32:32,200
["Think For A Minute" playing softly]

504
00:32:36,913 --> 00:32:38,915
♪ Something's going on ♪ 

505
00:32:39,123 --> 00:32:41,417
♪ A change is taking place ♪ 

506
00:32:42,210 --> 00:32:46,297
♪ Children smiling in the street 
Have gone without a trace ♪ 

507
00:32:46,631 --> 00:32:49,008
♪ This street used to be full ♪ 

508
00:32:49,092 --> 00:32:51,427
♪ It used to make me smile ♪

509
00:32:51,636 --> 00:32:54,389
♪ And now it seems that everyone 
